    "9c1cf209-15ac-4a1e-b6ad-3f306e8a0e6d": {
      "id": "9c1cf209-15ac-4a1e-b6ad-3f306e8a0e6d",
      "name": "Scene 1",
      "type": "writing",
      "kind": "scene",
      "content": "<p><strong>Part I - New Beginnings</strong></p><p><strong>CHAPTER 1 - King's Assassin</strong></p><p><br></p><p>Tims Caulder picked up a pebble and threw it hard. It sailed farther than he expected and landed in the nearby drain tunnel with a satisfying splash.</p><p>With a smile, he picked up a larger rock. This one sailed even further.</p><p>The dragon inside the black hole roared out his rage of being struck a defeating blow.</p><p>Smiling at the feat of destroying the latest threat, he fingered the lining of his pockets and produced a copper coin.</p><p>Master Brad had given him a few coins to go to market today. He wasn’t fool enough to believe it was out of charity. The brothel was expecting several high-class men and he wasn't to get in the way. Usually, he was quiet for the most part but curiosity and the age of 13 simply made him wander into places he shouldn't be in.</p><p>When mom died at the hands of one of Brad's clients, for some reason, he took it on himself to watch over Tims.</p><p>Tims knew he should have felt something when she died, but no tears came then and none would come now. He hardly knew the woman. The only memories he had were the few days she hadn't been drunk. She had talked angrily, shouting he was the reason she had no money. A woman with a kid was bad for business.</p><p>The next morning she was found naked in bed with a knife protruding from her chest. Most likely, one of her high paying clients had gotten angry and stabbed her. Like most similar scenes, investigations were swift and nothing was really done, chalking it up to a deal gone bad. Prostitutes were simply not important enough to waste time and money on.</p><p>His life fell into the hands of Brad for better or worse.</p><p>For the most part, he had no rules except one. Don't get into trouble.</p><p>Willow Town wasn't a big city but it was on one of Calmone's main highways. This meant it would get visitors from all different parts of the country, even from Sarsda, the capital city of Calmone.</p><p>By and large, he had explored all that Willow Town had to offer a young boy seeking adventure. He would climb the trees near the city garden and spy into the various windows of nobles who foolishly kept their windows open to him. Then there were the rooftops of all the closely built buildings. With the ease of a squirrel, he would climb the nearest tree with its limbs hanging out and jump to the nearest rooftop. Here, the entire city was at his fingertips. Even the few gated roads leading to the wealthier class citizens wasn't about to keep him out.</p><p>Right now however, he was in the drain pipes. The city could only hold his curiosity for so long. He wanted a real adventure. He wanted to explore beyond the reaches of Willow Town and climb the highest mountains.</p><p>Tims looked up from his meandering thoughts to the sound of clip-clops of several hooves.</p><p>Getting to his feet, he walked to the edge of the drain's opening to the river that flowed alongside the town’s border.</p><p>On a nearby bridge, he saw the first of many decorated horses. The riders in the front of a large caravan wore the garb every person in Calmone knew.</p><p>\"Black Knights!\" he whispered in awe. His heart pounded in anticipation of seeing them up close.</p><p>Black Knights were the elite soldiers known in the Five Kingdoms. Every child knew the name as they were sang about in tavern halls and Inns. Their feats were legendary, probably half made up but held in high regard. There were the normal soldiers that patrolled the Kingdom and then there were those whose very presence made people pause. Every so often, a performance would be put on in a town they stayed in. This was the Dance of Swords. The knight would display the unusual speed and expert use of the sword, making them the most talked about and dangerous soldier. It was said by many adults, this was the reason Calmone had such long years of peace. No other country within the five Kingdoms of Elise dared attack Calmone openly for fear of the Black Knights. These were the King's personal knights who made their rounds of the King’s Highways.</p><p>With quick sure steps, Tims stepped to the edge of the drain and expertly leaped to an outcropping below. He skirted the river bank to a large oak tree and expertly climbed. A few seconds later, he was sitting on the edge of a branch watching the procession.</p><p>When he would make his rounds in the brothel, the ladies often spoke of wishing to entertain a Black Knight or two. Their eyes would light up with laughter and in a group, would share dreamlike stories of these dashing, famed soldiers in the service to the King.</p><p>A year ago, he had just begun to experience what the women called an awakening. Their laughter caused him to blush heatedly and as the inevitable happened, he ran from the room. With their revealing clothes, he was filled with strange new thoughts he hadn't dreamed of till then.</p><p>That’s when he met Brandy.</p><p>She was a shy girl, a few years older than himself, who had been on the streets for most of her life. Her story was like most of the other women. They had no family and lived the street life, fighting to survive. For better coin, they displayed themselves on the street corners to whoever would pay.</p><p>Brad had taken her in after he had found her laying in a pool of blood near a heap of garbage. Her entire body had bruises and cuts all over. A deep gash ran the length of her face where someone had taken a knife intending to kill her.</p><p>He had overheard her the day before talking with another woman. Even though she wasn't a virgin, she was terrified by her last experience.</p><p>At a knock on his bedroom door, he opened it to find her standing there with only a silk cloth covering her. His eyes fell on her naked form. Nothing was concealed from him including deep scars that ran across her chest and abdomen and the blemish that ran halfway across her face.</p><p>His heart pounded loud in his chest and his blood boiled with excitement.</p><p>In a strange, sudden embarrassment, he closed his eyes. Shame washed over him and he didn't know why. He had been around these women all his life. There was nothing he hadn't seen before and many times, wondered what it would be like having sex with any number of Brad’s women who would walk around half-naked, teasing him.</p><p>But when it came to Brandy, he saw the scars on her face. He could see the deep stab wounds in her stomach from someone who wanted her but not a baby.</p><p>Something changed in him as he looked at her. It was so deep, all thought of taking her to his bed vanished. She was a victim in a man's world. She had been used and like anything unwanted, beaten and left for dead. To claim a child of a prostitute was the worst thing to have.</p><p>Feeling the pain intimately, he hung his head.</p><p>Brandy’s eyes scrunched into worried creases. She hung her own head and quickly covered herself with her hands. With tears suddenly running down her face, she barely got out a choked whisper. “I’m sorry I disappointed you.” She turned quickly to run from him.</p><p>Tims snapped his head up and called out, “Brandy!” He heard the terrified, self-condemning tone in her voice and it pierced him like nothing else had.</p><p>She froze in the doorway, trembling. She refused to look at him.</p><p>Getting up quickly, he reached for a nearby blanket and draped it over her naked body. He knew she couldn’t leave him so quickly. If she did, word would reach Brad and that was never a good thing.</p><p>Taking her by the hand, he led her into the room and to the bed where he sat down and patted the mattress beside him. Hesitantly, he said, “Can we just talk?”</p><p>Brandy hesitantly lowered herself to the mattress before hanging her head again. “I’m ugly. Just say it!” She shook again, this time with an escaped whimper of a cry. “I’ll be kicked out now. Nobody is going to want me.”</p><p>Tims found her hands and clasped them in his own. In a whisper, he said, “You’re beautiful, Brandy.”</p><p>She turned towards him with a glare. “Don’t lie to me, Tims! If I were beautiful, we wouldn’t be sitting here. You’d be inside me and I’d be your first experience.” She turned away and crossed her arms in a glare.”</p><p>He took several breaths. Everything in him screamed. Here was a girl practically giving herself to him. And he was having a moral crisis now?</p><p>Calming his heart, he waited several seconds before saying, “I want you, Brandy. I really do. But…” He looked up, and with a finger, traced the deep scar across her face. “You’re a victim. I can’t do this, knowing it’s what has caused you to be afraid.”</p><p>For a long moment, Brandy stared hard at him, uncertain. Again, tears began spilling and she closed her eyes tight.</p><p>He instinctively reached out and pulled her to himself, holding her as she sobbed in deep racking gasps.</p><p>When the tears subsided, he kept holding her.</p><p>Slowly, she began to open up and before long, they were talking, trading dreams of what ifs and the future. They talked of everything except what she was there for.</p><p>It was late when she left Tims’ bedroom and at the door, she just looked at him. In a soft voice, she said, “If you ever want me, just ask. I won’t say no.”</p><p>She never came to him afterward, and he never asked her to.</p><p>The fact he had talked to Brandy instead of having sex found its way to Brad's ears.</p><p>Brad never said a word but his attitude towards him changed dramatically. To Brad, anyone who refused a woman's advances wasn't worth being around. Tims became a waste of space and Brad made certain he knew it.</p><p>Which was why Brad had him gone today. The clients were too important for someone like him to mess things up.</p><p>His train of thought filtered back to the caravan. He counted at least ten guards in the front of the main carriage. The highly decorated outer surface sparkled in the sunlight.</p><p>To his curious mind, he pieced together what he had heard in taverns and the talk of the town. The highway through Willow Town was a direct route to the royal estates on the lake of Vilac, some leagues south of the city. Obviously, they were heading north on their way back from visiting King Joshua's sister, Duchess Emil.</p><p>Tims tried to peer into the carriage windows below, but the heavy curtains were drawn closed.</p><p>The train of horses and carriages turned then down Silver Lane where most of the wealthier class lived. No doubt they would be staying at the Fisher King's Inn. The owner didn't care too much for him. He was too poor to be of anyone significant.</p><p>As the caravan disappeared from another bend in the road, he sighed heavily.</p><p>\"I wish I was someone else.\" He looked down at his dirty shirt and pants. He wasn't the poorest in Willow Town but close to it. Brad had a reputation to uphold with the clients frequenting the brothel. So long as he was fed once a day and had semi-decent clothes to wear, Brad left him to do whatever he wanted. The only exception was the occasional tending to a lady or two when needed.</p><p>Each day dragged on endlessly.</p><p>He might as well be a beggar, Tims thought darkly. He slipped from the oak tree to the ground below.</p><p>Maybe he would get lucky today and see the King from a rooftop.</p><p>He made his way up the bank and to one of the trees he frequently used. Climbing through the tangle of limbs and larger branches, he reached the second-highest branch. From here, he felt the mountain wind blow through his hair. He walked the length of the branch to where the roof of Gerald's bakery stood. At this time of day, the chimney was puffing smoke out with the sweet fragrance of spiced bread.</p><p>Ignoring the hunger pangs leaping up, he focused on the roof.</p><p>He was suddenly the daring Black Knight who was rescuing the princess and her family.</p><p>The branch bobbed up and down, and he realized he had gained more weight.</p><p>Taking several deep breaths, he eyed the rooftop once, twice...</p><p>He leaped.</p><p>Landing on his feet, he looked up at the darkening sky. Time was not on his side. The sun was quickly fading. Soon, the night sky would take over and rooftop escapades wouldn't be as fun but dangerous. He had done that once before and fell hard. Brad was furious and scolded him endlessly. After a week of being laid up in bed and Brad's ranting at having to care for a useless whelp, he never attempted rooftops at night.</p><p>The rooftop led to another rooftop then another. From his vantage point, he was on top of the world looking down on the little people. He was the invincible Black Knight!</p><p>Following Silver Lane road from roof to roof, the Fisher King's Inn came into view.</p><p>Tims paused his running on the roof of Tiny Tips Tailor. He never liked the clothes that were displayed inside. The atmosphere was too stuffy and the people buying acted as if they owned the entire town which they didn't. He knew several of the kids that ran through the streets. They were no better than he was.</p><p>From another alley, the scent of sweetness filtered his way. Again, hunger pangs shot through his stomach, making him hungry all over again. Maybe he should just turn down Keeper's Grove to home where he knew a few scraps of bread and meat were kept for him. But the Inn was only a few blocks away now!</p><p>The princess had to be rescued!</p><p>The stalwart knight ran on.</p><p>Lanterns lit the main drive as it wound its way through the Fisher King's Inn elegant landscape of apple trees and pine groves. From his view overlooking the walled-in lawn, he was at a loss. The gatehouse was guarded against those like him.</p><p>Coming to a stop, he spotted an overhanging branch of a maple tree. Its limbs were close enough that he could jump onto it. Its limbs spread out over the wall towards a nearby stable.</p><p>\"Then what?\" he wondered aloud. He took several long breaths in and out from the bout of running. By now, everyone had to be inside dining on the finest meals in the country. From far off, he could hear the soft laughter of entertainment. The carriage he had seen earlier had undoubtedly beat him here. There was nobody to see now.</p><p>The world of the Black Knight vanished and Tims was himself again, a nobody who dreamed of impossible things.</p><p>Hanging his head, he turned to run back the way he had come.</p><p>A sudden movement caught his eye and he watched as two men ran across the lawn keeping clear of the lanterns being lit. Dusk was here and in a matter of minutes, night would take over.</p><p>He followed the two men with his eyes. They were clearly sneaking across the grass. When they reached the stables, they disappeared on the other side.</p><p>Tims narrowed his eyes. These men weren't Kingsmen. Their clothes didn't fit what he had seen many times before. They also ran like thieves and he knew all about that. In the brothels, the women at times told him stories of their previous lives. There was always a callused tone to the stories that never sat well with him. The women were like sisters to him. Brandy, being closest to his age, would warm up at times. Out of need more than anything else, she would retell an event where she would steal for the group she belonged to. It never ended well and he winced when she retold in a cold, indifferent tone, how Rat would count out what she handed over. In an evil grin, he would scream, \"What is this! This is only half of your dues, mouse!\" A sinister smile would creep onto his face. \"You owe me.\"</p><p>Brandy turned her head, not able to look at him. \"His goons would pin me down, and he would do what he wanted.\" Tears would spill from her cheeks only once before a hardness filled her. \"Here, I choose where and when some man enters me. And I get paid for it.\"</p><p>Tims knew he couldn’t stay living the way he was. One day, Brad would get tired of him and kick him to the streets for good. He had already found several spots he could hold up in when that day came. A few of the women even gave tips for street life. Brandy was quick to tell him which gangs to stay away from and those who were the safest. Rat, of course, was one to stay far removed from. It didn't matter if you were a boy or a girl.</p><p>Tims’s meandering thoughts were pulled back to the present. From the stables, a glint of steel flashed in a nearby lantern's light. He frowned and peered more closely through the tree branches. Not thinking about what he was doing, he stepped to the edge of the roof and grabbed hold of an overhanging branch.</p><p>He pulled himself up and shimmied to the middle of the tree. A natural curve in the branch made for a good foothold. For a brief instant, he wondered what it would be like to climb to the top of the maple tree and look out.</p><p>Somewhere in the back of his mind, another thought took shape and crushed his wanderings.</p><p>What are you doing here? If you get caught, Brad will not get you out of trouble. You will be flung into prison for breaking the law!</p><p>\"I'll be seen as a thief,\" Tims whispered the words out loud. He closed his eyes and envisioned the various women he had come to know with their stories. If he were caught now, that was his future. Brad would kick him out for sure.</p><p>Something in the distance caught the corner of his eye.</p><p>He turned and looked back the way he had come.</p><p>The outline of another carriage showed in the darkness. Two lantern lights floated in the blackness with two soldiers in front.</p><p>He looked to the stables and then back at the carriage on the bridge. A sinking feeling fell over him as something dawned.</p><p>Had the King already gone into the Inn or was he in the carriage on the bridge? He couldn't possibly know that answer but what if?</p><p>\"Stupid! Stupid! Stupid!\" Tims berated himself. \"Stay out of it!\" But inside his gut, he felt a wrongness well up. Something bad was going to happen. And he was a witness to this thing.</p><p>\"I can't do anything about it!\" He glared and all sense of being a Black Knight washed away. Who was he kidding? He was nobody important.</p><p>Time seemed to slow down. The carriage drew closer and closer.</p><p>He glared and looked towards the stables.</p><p>He looked back at the outline of the carriage strolling down the road.</p><p>What could he possibly do to make a difference?</p><p>Closing his eyes tight, Tims prayed to Kata, the spirit god who oversaw these things. \"I pray you see me this night. Guide me now.\"</p><p>Blocking all the warnings filtering into his brain, he walked to the edge of the branch. The stable roof was just in reach.</p><p>He jumped.</p><p>His feet caught the surface of the roof with a soft \"thud\" before freezing in place. His heart thudded loud in his chest.</p><p>When nobody came storming out of the stables, he breathed, realizing he was holding his breath this whole time.</p><p>Now what?</p><p>He had no idea what to do. These guys were probably trained assassins. He was a 12 year old boy who had never stepped foot outside of Willow Town. For the hundredth time today, he felt impossibly small and insignificant.</p><p>Sitting down, he hung his head as the weight of what was about to happen daunted him.</p><p>After what seemed an eternity, the clip-clop of hooves sounded on cobbled stones.</p><p>From the nearby gatehouse, two men in livery suits ran up a flight of stairs where a platform held levers and gears. The grinding of metal chains and counterweights was heard as the iron gates lifted.</p><p>Tims squinted his eyes to see better. Two lanterns bobbed in the blackness before the carriage but the shape and type was hidden. Maybe it wasn't the King.</p><p>The coachman, silhouetted by the two lanterns, was masked in a thick scarf and hat. The cold winds of the Whiteface Mountains had pushed into Calmone for a blast of mountain air with the nights growing bitter cold. Just behind the carriage, four more soldiers sat in their saddles.</p><p>Six guards for one carriage?</p><p>Tims' heart beat hard. Slowly, he made it across the stable roof. Nearing the chimney, he caught sight of someone at the other edge of the roof. The man was laying on his belly with a crossbow in his hands. An arrow was notched and pulled back.</p><p>He frantically scanned the rest of the rooftop, but the second assassin was nowhere to be seen.</p><p>What do I do? he screamed silently. His heart beat so hard it had to give him away any second.</p><p>The assassin was like a statue.</p><p>The carriage was past the gatehouse and turned a corner in the road on its way to the Inn's main entrance.</p><p>The assassin turn slightly to aim more perfectly. He sighted the carriage and lifted a finger readying to release the arrow. From inside the man's hand, a ball of fire erupted, igniting something at the tip of the arrow.</p><p>Tims ran without thinking and screamed, \"Assassin!\"</p><p>He leaped the same instant the assassin's finger flicked a trigger.</p><p>His twelve year old body rammed into the man's crouching form the same moment the arrow flew in a blaze of fire.</p><p>The man rolled and with quick deftness, grabbed hold of his neck and squeezed hard.</p><p>His lungs immediately siezed as air was cut off to the rest of his body. Tims violently kicked to free himself but the man held a lot more mass than his scrawny form. He kicked again and again trying desperately to land a blow.</p><p>The assassin struggled to his feet, still holding him by the neck. The man’s eyes glared with hate at being caught by a whelp.</p><p>Tims felt his vision quickly going dim. He could feel his body slowly losing the will to fight back.</p><p>The man dangled him over the edge of the roof, squeezing harder. Tims knew he wasn’t getting out of this alive. The man’s eyes told him all he needed to know. His throat was going to snap before he dropped.</p><p>With little air left and blotches of red coloring over his eyes, he leaned backwards deliberately and kicked as hard as he could.</p><p>By a miracle, his feet landed hard against the man’s legs causing him to lose his balance. In a stifled cry of alarm, the man let go.</p><p>Tims’ world tilted and spun in a dizzy array. He cried out, realizing what he had just done.</p><p>From somewhere in the distance, a giant explosion lit the night. A few seconds later, another explosion spewed stone and blood through the air.</p><p>Screams of men and horses alike sounded behind the carriage. Soldiers were thrown from their mounts as stone debris ripped through their bodies. Fire engulfed three of the four rear guards.</p><p>Tims landed in a pile of hay beneath the roof.</p><p>The assassin landed just beside him and scrambling to his feet, darted from the stable yard with a second man right beside him.</p><p>Gasping for air, he raised his head to see the carriage was still intact. The first explosion had happened several yards beyond the carriage.</p><p>A man shouted, \"There! Seize him!\"</p><p>One of the guards from the gatehouse was already galloping towards the stables while one of the two guards in front of the carriage took off after the two fleeing assassins.</p><p>Two more guards poured out from the carriage and ran towards the stables.</p><p>On spotting Tims in the bale of hay, one of the guards drew his sword and ran towards him. Closing the distance in remarkable speed, the guard shouted, “You!” The point of his sword leveled dangerously close to Tims’ already soar neck.</p><p>The guard paused in mid-sentence, blinking stupidly. \"A boy?\" The man asked incredulously. His eyes were raised in disbelief. He shook his head before saying, \"Were you the one who warned us of these men?\"</p><p>Tims nodded mutely, still trying to get his lungs to work properly.</p><p>The guard looked back at the fire and the three men who lay on the ground now being attended by others. From the Inn's entrance, more soldiers poured out, running towards the fires.</p><p>Lowering his sword, the guard asked gently, \"What is your name, boy?\" He extended a hand towards him and after a hesitant pause, accepted.</p><p>The grip was firm like a rock as he was pulled out of the hay and on firm ground.</p><p>When the guard noticed Tims wasn’t forthcoming, he repeated but more firmly this time. “Young man, what is your name?”</p><p>He hesitated before saying, \"Tims…Tims Caulder.\" He paused before quickly adding, \"Sir!\"</p><p>The guard nodded briefly. He let a few seconds pass before saying, \"Do you know who you have saved tonight?\"</p><p>Tims shook his head, not sure how to respond. Should he say yes?</p><p>\"Come with me, young man.\"</p><p>He blinked in startlement. \"Sir?\"</p><p>The guard didn't back down. \"Now, boy. Come with me.\" His gloved hands locked around his own and led the way to where a gathering crowd of soldiers piled around the carriage.</p><p>Two of the guards that had been with the carriage returned on their horses. They wore the famed black armor.</p><p>One knight said in an angry voice, \"I only saw two men running. We won't be getting answers from them though. They killed themselves before we could catch them.\".</p><p>\"Well that's too bad.\" The man holding Tims said coldly. He wore a gruff facial expression. His chiseled face was like a statue's. Everything about him was hard. \"I wanted to make them squeal as they talked!\" He turned to the door of the carriage. \"Joshua! We have a guest you will want to meet.\"</p><p>Tims frowned. He didn't know much about etiquette in political circles but if he was guessing right, he was about to meet the King. And this man called him by his first name.</p><p>The door of the carriage opened and a man dressed in a rich cream-colored tunic stepped down to the ground. Over the tunic was a finely stitched deep blue satin overcoat with gold fringes. His boots were polished to fit the rest of the man's attire complete with a swirling purple cape. His face was much calmer than the man holding him. It was almost too calm for someone who had just avoided death.</p><p>The man eyed him up and down. In a deep frown of confusion, he said, \"Do you know who I am, boy?\"</p><p>Tims nodded. \"I...think so, sir. King Joshua?\"</p><p>King Joshua's lips parted in a slight smile. \"Yes, boy. And if it is to be believed, you are why I am still alive.\"</p><p>He hung his head. \"I...I just did what anyone would do, sir.\"</p><p>At this, a few in the crowd laughed.</p><p>\"Indeed?\" the King replied. He turned to the man who found him. \"Stingar, what is it you saw again?\"</p><p>\"Well, I thought I saw a man take a leap from the roof dragging down an assassin.\" He looked at Tims curiously. \"Maybe a man at heart.\" He laughed and pounded him on the shoulder hard.</p><p>King Joshua stood there a second more, his eyes fixed on him.</p><p>Tims felt his insides turn. He wanted to run. He hated anyone staring at him. He was nothing to look at.</p><p>At last, the King said, \"I see something in you, Tims. Something extraordinary.\"</p><p>Tims kept his head bowed, feeling the heat of the King’s word sear into his worthless heart.</p><p>\"Look at me, boy,\" the King commanded.</p><p>He looked up trying to hide the emotions he felt.</p><p>\"I owe you my life for what you did.\" The words came hard as a matter of fact. \"I will not forget this.\"</p><p>Turning to his men, the King stepped over to where his fallen men lay.</p><p>In the light of the still-burning fire, Tims caught the sudden raw emotion of pain wash over his King. The man knelt gently towards the three who had died. Their faces were a mask of pain with their bodies twisted from the blast.</p><p>To Stingar, Joshua's words were harsh and cold. \"I want to know who these assassins are. I want to know everything!\"</p><p>Turning back to Tims, the king said a bit more calmly, \"How did you come to be behind the one assassin on the roof?\"</p><p>He hesitated before recounting the evening leading up to spying on the two men sneaking into the Fisher King Inn's stable yard.</p><p>The King shook his head. \"And you decided right then and there what needed to be done? Thank the gods for young boys and curiosity.\"</p><p>After a few more pleasantries, he found his way out of the sight of the King’s men. This whole ordeal was surreal and unnerving! What he wanted now was to be back home and in bed.</p><p>Sneaking away from all the commotion, Tims quietly made his way back to the main roads and the long walk home.</p><p>Much later that night in bed, he dreamed of trees, of a wolf and eagle, of Kings and princesses. And of Tims, the great protector of the realm.</p>",
