    "b8d6ebc1-be00-487c-92bc-fb2f2e55bc27": {
      "id": "b8d6ebc1-be00-487c-92bc-fb2f2e55bc27",
      "name": "1",
      "type": "writing",
      "kind": "scene",
      "content": "<p><strong>CHAPTER 3 - Princess Secrets</strong></p><p><br></p><p>The first few years were the hardest.</p><p>Tims had his fair share of bullies who saw him as nothing more than a bastard. Nothing he did would change that. Master Richard's threats to those who bullied were met with more secretive means of attacking Tims. It was something he slowly accepted as part of life here in the capital and little by little, he built a wall around his heart towards such things. All he could do was work hard and show Master Richards that he wasn't a worthless servant.</p><p>It wasn't all bad working in the stables. He loved the time he spent brushing down the horses, sometimes even spending long hours at night sitting in the hay lofts gazing up between a few cracks in the rafters. The stars were companions to his endless dreams. He knew he was an outcast. Nothing was going to change that fact. In fact, it made doing what he wanted easier, not constantly being bothered by friends.</p><p>When chores were done for the morning, he was given a few hours to himself, and he used them every chance he got.</p><p>With a few coins in his pocket, he ventured into the city streets, exploring to his heart’s content. So much of Sarsda was still new to him. Its vastness called to him to walk its many stone streets, to look at the buildings reaching into the heavens. He would make his way down one street then the next till at week's end, he had explored every part of a district. His mind played out imaginary scenarios where he would find a creature of myth he had to fight to save the kingdom. The next week, he would venture down another area till at year's end, he had explored a vast amount of Sarsda's grand city.</p><p>He had discovered to his delight, the city held secrets, ancient and forgotten alleys that had been abandoned for hundreds of years. Here, he would explore the old streets that had been built over and cemented up for more modern roadways or buildings. Every so often though, a crack was found in alley walls and Tims' curiosity exploded, a deep need to step through the dark hole and explore the strange abandoned labyrinth of ancient roads and their mysterious destinations. Most times, these were shortcuts to other places within the city that he used regularly.</p><p>Despite his many new adventures within Sarsda, Tims had trouble making friends. The rude and mocking tone towards him eventually dulled down to more snide and whispered remarks. But finding someone his own age to hang out with was far and in between. When living in Willow Town, his world consisted of the streets and the women of the brothel. Sure, they weren’t exactly friends but at least they didn’t look down on him each day. Here, he was acutely aware of his life before the stables. Each time a lord or lady came calling to ready their carriage or someone just wanted a little exercise, he saw it. The looks each noble lord gave him sent shivers down his spine. Obviously, what King Joshua gifted him with was a well known thing among the nobles. The looks of disgust and sometimes outright hate made him hang his head in shame.</p><p>The first few times this occurred, Daniel had stood back, not wanting to get into trouble with the powerful lords. One misspoken word, and they could make his life miserable or worse.</p><p>When Lord Darson came to the stables one morning, he was with five of his men, geared up to go hunting. He had overseen the latest trades with Percvam in several dyes and furs and was anxious to be out hunting. He normally was cooped up in his offices overseeing the merchant fleets he controlled. The scent in the autumn air filled everyone with restlessness. Darson's personality was like many of the other nobles who did little but bully others with his station. Knowing how much power he held over the trading guilds, he never let down on showing it to others. Tims had a suspicion that Darson never really sailed himself or traveled to other lands when broking a deal with the neighboring traders unless absolutely necessary. In fact, he probably didn't know what labor really was. He probably didn’t even know how to swing a sword despite having soldiers that accompanied his fleets and trade wagons.</p><p>The morning had begun cold with a brush of wind from the Whiteface Mountains far to the east. Hurrying to saddle the six horses Darson requested, he and Daniel were strapping the last remaining saddle belts.</p><p>Lord Darson and his five men strode into the stable yard when something flickered in Darson’s eyes on spotting Tims doing a final check on his saddle. With a glare, Darson said, “Don’t touch my horse, you worthless piece of scum!” His glare turned on Daniel. “You! Take care of my horse. I don’t want my saddle snapping while hunting!” His glare leveled on Tims, gave a hacking sound before spitting a large gob of phlegm, landing inches from Tims' boots.</p><p>Tims let the words slide by as he had done so many times before. This wasn’t the worst treatment he had gotten and wouldn’t be the last. He backed away with head lowered, knowing not to look the lord in the face. Doing so had gotten a back handed slap before.</p><p>Daniel quickly took his place, prepping Darson’s mount, checking the tackle and sturdiness of the saddle. With a sidelong glance at Tims he said, “Sir, Tims’ work is more than proficient here. He’s one of the hardest workers we have with excellent skills with the horses.”</p><p>The look Lord Darson gave Daniel could turn water to ice.</p><p>Daniel just shook his head. “You’re wrong to treat him so badly.”</p><p>Tims closed his eyes, groaning silently. Wrong words, Daniel!</p><p>Immediately, someone in Darson’s party stepped forward, his own face glowering. “How dare you talk back to your betters, you insolent whelp!” He was carrying a riding whip with him and leveled it at Daniel.</p><p>Daniel took a step back, his eyes going wide.</p><p>“For your sticking up for this pet of the King’s, I’m going to-“</p><p>“You’re going to do what?” A familiar feminine voice called out from behind. The tone had a threatening coldness to it.</p><p>Everyone turned to watch as Princess Averin, accompanied by her friend Eseme, rounded the corner of the stable halls. She was wearing a flowing white tunic and leather riding pants. Eseme, on the other hand, wore her usual decked out gown of some rich noble.</p><p>Averin wore a neutral expression but Tims swore he saw in her eyes the hint of rage beginning to ignite.</p><p>Darson’s hands clamped over his friend's arm and the whip lowered. In a cold voice, Lord Darson said, “My Princess, how lovely to see you here this morning.” He gave a slight bow that did nothing to clear the chills running up and down Tims’ spine. For whatever reason, he felt a deep need to run and stand in front of the princess as Lord Darson looked at her.</p><p>Averin turned her gaze on Daniel then on himself, a warmth immediately flooding his heart. Her expressionless eyes slowly lit on seeing him and she smiled. “I’ve come for our morning ride, Tims.” She turned immediately to the horse Daniel had been checking and with a hard jerk of the saddle, another glance at the buckles, she remarked, “Nobody will be falling from this saddle except an idiot who doesn’t know how to ride.” She said this while eyeing Lord Darson with a glare. Turning to Eseme beside her, she said, “Thank you for our lovely walk this morning, Eseme.”</p><p>Eseme gave a shake of her head. “I’ll be in the sun room with the ladies of Vilac. They have many interesting things to gossip about the south and their women.”</p><p>The princess shook her head with a sigh before grinning. “And I will be spending my morning soaking up the sun on the back of a horse.” She laughed at Eseme’s eye rolling before leaving.</p><p>By now, Lord Darson was glaring at nothing in particular. “By your leave, my lady,” he said in as much neutrality as he could muster, “we will be off to our hunt.”</p><p>Averin nodded slightly. “Good hunting to you and hope nobody falls accidentally.” Her smile lacked warmth and the glare returned on the Lord’s face. He mounted his horse in a fluid motion before yelling a command. In seconds, he and his men were gone.</p><p>As soon as they were out of hearing distance, Averin's face turned dark. “I hope you do fall and break something.” She spit in their direction so unladylike.</p><p>Tims couldn’t hold back and laughed out loud.</p><p>This got the princess chuckling before she laughed too.</p><p>“You two…” Daniel shook his head. He wore a smile trying not to laugh.</p><p>Realizing what had just happened, Tims turned to Daniel and said in all seriousness, “Thank you. You didn’t have to stick up for me though.”</p><p>Daniel rose an eyebrow. “You need someone on your side among all these…” He hesitated and glanced at where the princess stood. “Snakes.”</p><p>Averin’s eyebrows lifted a little at Daniel. “Were you going to say something else?”</p><p>Daniel coughed and blushed. “Uh, no, my lady.”</p><p>With a shake of her head, whipping her braided hair back, Averin gave a mischievous smile. “If you haven’t figured it out yet, I’m not one of the ladies.” She gave a devilish smile. “So don’t act like I am when I’m here.”</p><p>Daniel let out a breath and looked at Tims. “I think we’re in trouble.”</p><p>Tims’ eyes brightened. “I like trouble.”</p><p>They all laughed and just like that, a strange sort of bond began to form among the three of them.</p><p>As time went on, the name calling died down even more till in its place was a slow build of grudging respect by other stable hands and couriers who held apartments close to the stables. They all ate with each other in the mess hall and as Tims' presence and hard work was seen, there simply couldn't be any remarks except respectful. The couriers, who were always in the stables, began to see Tims as a kindred brother, one who was looked down on for their station. And still, he held his head high, doing his work diligently despite the nobles who showed up and made his life miserable.</p><p>None of this was lost on Master Richards. He had worn a scowl every time he crossed paths with Tims the first year. He would look at Daniel overseeing Tims' training and then walk away without a word.</p><p>As with the stable hand and couriers though, Master Richards gradually came around and the scowl on his face disappeared. In its place was a firm but trusting look. He even had a few words with a noble or two who got it in their heads that whipping Tims would be a fun sport. The glare and look of murder in Richard's eyes, not to mention the King had the ear of his princess, and that quickly stopped.</p><p>True to her word, Princess Averin kept coming back to the pasture fields each morning. She would give every effort to make time for Daniel and Tims, to simply talk and laugh. Their friendship grew in leaps and bounds. And as if it were something she personally had to do, she trained Tims on horsemanship, not letting anyone else do it. In this way, she spent most mornings with him, coaching while laughing about the simple antics he made.</p><p>He was already in his saddle one morning, ready for the morning’s lessons when Averin rode up beside him, beaming a mischievous smile. \"Are you ready to fly?\" She laughed at his bleak look of shock. \"Oh come on, it's fun!\" she laughed again and without warning, swatted Tims' mare with a shout.</p><p>The mare bucked gently before taking off at a gallop. Tims gripped the reigns tightly, his face turning pale at the sudden increase of the horse's speed.</p><p>With a shout of glee, Averin laughed and galloped after him, easily passing and led them on a merry chase.</p><p>From behind, Tims shouted, clinging desperately to the reigns as his mare follow behind Averin’s ever-increasing speed.</p><p>He was 14 and had grown in more ways than one. His height had increased, his face slowly shedding the boyish look with a more thin and muscular build from working in the stables. With Averin's close tutelage, he was even becoming as experienced in horses as herself.</p><p>The fresh morning winds washed over his face as his horse galloped across the plains. He drank in the sights and smells as the summer months was closing and the harvest season approached. He loved this time of year. Everything changed, and it stirred something inside like he wanted to simply take his horse and explore the furthest reaches of the country. He lifted his hands high and tilted his head back, taking in everything with a shout of laughter. He was one with the horse!</p><p>Beside him, Princess Averin's own mount's hooves dug into the grassy turf, and she gave a shout of pure joy, mimicking Tims with a giant smile. She never displayed such a thing so openly except when they were alone together.</p><p>They rode across the grass fields letting their horses have their way for a full hour, the ride Averin leading them on to be extra long. New landmarks were being spotted and Tims wondered what was up. Averin asked yesterday for him to get up a little earlier this morning so they could watch the sun rise. But this was taking their morning ride out of the pastures past the city walls and into the northern plains. He had only ventured here a few times with Averin and only for a short time. This ride had taken them much further. He wondered if the King even knew how far his daughter was riding with only a stable hand as an escort.</p><p>Princess Averin reigned her mount into a canter now as the plains ahead ended at a cliff edge overlooking the Rock River. In the distance they could see the beginning of the Drysin Sea far on the horizon.</p><p>To the east across the plains of Calmone, the sun began to peak over the dark green forests that lined the plains.</p><p>Slowing at last to a halt, Averin dismounted and grabbed a blanket from the satchel, laying it down in the wet morning dew. With Tims' help, she lowered herself into a sitting position before he sat next to her, taking in the sight of the morning rays of sun cascading over the pastures and hills. Ahead, seagulls cried out, soaring in the sky.</p><p>After a long, hesitating pause, Tims said, \"Won't people be worried about you? I mean this is further out than what we usually ride.\"</p><p>Averin gave him a sidelong glance and laughed. \"Oh please! Everybody knows me. I do what I want when I want.\"</p><p>\"I know,\" Tims smiled, \"but we're miles now from the city. We have no escort.\" He knew he wasn't about to convince her this was unwise. He knew from experience and the overheard rumors. She was her father's child, taking after him. King Joshua was the same way. He saw her give him a frown and a raised eyebrow. \"Don't be acting like my mother, Tims.\"</p><p>Tims just sighed and leaned back on his hands, content to watch the sun rise with her. He felt the warmth of her companionship flood him. There was nowhere else he wanted to be right now. Even Daniel didn't get this type of treatment from Averin. This was something just between the two of them.</p><p>At last, Averin glanced at him with a smile then back at the sunrise.</p><p>\"What was that for?\"</p><p>She giggled. \"I have a secret.\" She paused. \"It's why I had us come out here. We should talk about it.\"</p><p>Tims pretended to frown. \"What secret is that? Is it a good or bad secret?\"</p><p>\"Oh, a good secret!\" she laughed and turned to face him. \"Want to know what it is?\"</p><p>\"Of course I do!\" he laughed in turn. \"What is it?\"</p><p>Averin literally rocked back and forth, her eyes beaming. \"Ok, here it is. Ready?\"</p><p>Tims sighed heavily. \"Out with it, girl! I'm dying here!\"</p><p>\"I was talking with father yesterday.\"</p><p>She paused.</p><p>\"And?\"</p><p>\"We're going to see each other a lot more! You and I!\" She turned to him, her face practically beaming with laughter and squeezed his hands.</p><p>Tims frowned. \"What do you mean?\" Since the incident with Lord Darson, despite the quieting of the stable hands and couriers, the dark looks he had gotten from nobles increased. Nobody heckled him mercilessly but still, he knew just by their glares how they saw him. He also knew the rumors spreading about Averin. She had taken a fancy with a stable hand.</p><p>A few months ago, Master Richards had come to him one night before bed and said, \"I have seen the good you do, boy. I am impressed, really.\" He paused and looked at the floor. He scratched at his mustache, something Tims caught on as an instinctual thing Richards did when he found something uncomfortable to talk about. \"I must warn you, however. The word is that you and the King's daughter are hanging out an awful lot.\"</p><p>Tims was taking out a fresh pair of clothes from the chest he was given for tomorrow morning's ride. His room wasn't furnished with luxurious things. In fact it had very few things other than a bed and chest.</p><p>Not looking up, he said, \"Everyone knows Averin and I go each morning for a ride.\" He was so used to calling the princess by her name, he rarely used her title as everyone else did.</p><p>Richard gave him a stern look and shook his head. \"She is also going to be turning 16.\" When it didn't register on Tims what Richards was implying, he sighed and looked Tims hard in the eyes. \"Tims, the princess is going to have suitors courting her shortly. It is not good that she is seen spending most of her mornings with...\" he shrugged, not able to find kinder words, \"a stable boy.\"</p><p>Tims looked down at his feet not knowing how to respond.</p><p>\"That's all I have to say, Tims.\" Richards patted him on the shoulder. \"If there is one thing I have faith in, it's that you will be honest with yourself.\" He walked out of the room.</p><p>He still remembered that talk, especially now. He had shoved it aside when nothing came of Richard's words. But now...</p><p>He looked Averin in the eyes. \"What do you mean, Averin? Why will we be seeing each other more?\"</p><p>Averin's eyes drew together slightly. \"Don't you want to?\" She looked a little hurt.</p><p>He smiled, reassuringly. \"Of course! I look forward to our morning rides. You brighten my day.\"</p><p>She smiled. \"Good! Because I talked with my father. Did you know he has been watching you?\"</p><p>His heart thudded hard with Richard's words coming back full force.</p><p>\"He is?\" he asked, trying to cover the sudden dread in his stomach.</p><p>Averin laughed out loud and gently pushed him. \"It's nothing to worry about! I assure you! You will love what is planned.\"</p><p>\"Planned?\" Tims blinked. \"Who planned it? Because if you did, I can bet it won't be good!\"</p><p>Averin smacked him a bit harder this time on the head. \"Is that any way to talk to your princess?\"</p><p>\"Hey, Master Richards says to be honest.\" Tims smiled and leaped off the blanket running.</p><p>\"Why you no good-\" Averin shot back and leaped after Tims but he was already back in his saddle. Calling down, he said, \"I'm hungry and you didn't bring food! See? I was right!\"</p><p>Averin huffed and rolled the blanket up stuffing it into the saddle bag. Leaping into her saddle she said, \"Wait till I get my hands on you!\"</p><p>\"If you can catch me!\" Tims laughed and kicked his horse into a gallop.</p><p>With Averin close behind, they raced back to Sarsda.</p><p>Tims woke with a start.</p><p>Blinking back the crust of sleep, he looked out the small window of his bed chamber seeing it was still dark out. Frowning, he wondered what had startled him awake.</p><p>Something tapped on the other side of the bedroom door.</p><p>Bleary eyed, he got up and wrapped his night robe about him before opening the door a crack.</p><p>In the candlelight of a lantern, Princess Averin's face shown. \"Tims,\" she whispered, \"We need to talk.\"</p><p>Frowning, he opened the door a little wider.</p><p>He blinked as Averin stepped into the chamber. She was wearing a shawl around herself that only half concealed she was dressed in a simple tunic and men's pants.</p><p>She paid no heed to his staring and went straight to the bed and sat down.</p><p>Tims closed the door softly and returned to stare at Averin's strange appearance. Only half awake, he yawned, saying, \"What needs to be talked about at this hour? Can't it wait till we ride out in a few hours?\"</p><p>She didn't look at him but focused her eyes on her folded hands in her lap. \"You won't be riding out with me this morning.\" Before he could ask anything, she continued. \"Two Black Knights are going to escort you to the palace.\"</p><p>Tims' heart thudded hard. \"Oh.\" His eyes grew round as Richard's words cemented into him fearful ideas.</p><p>Averin shook her head at his expression. Grabbing his hand in her own, she said softly, \"There is nothing to fear, Tims! It's nothing like that.\"</p><p>\"Then why am I going to be escorted to the palace?\"</p><p>\"Because, remember when I told you I had a secret two days ago?\"</p><p>\"Yeah,\" he glared. \"The one you never told me anything about.\"</p><p>\"I'm here because I want to make certain that secret is in your liking.\" She patted a spot on the bed beside her and motioned for him to sit with her.</p><p>As he took a seat next to her, Averin took his hand in her own again. \"Since you've arrived in Sarsda, I've convinced my father to look hard into you, to see you the way I see you.\" She paused. \"My father is going to break with tradition. He's going to name you, Tims!\"</p><p>\"Name me?\" Tims frowned, not understanding.</p><p>\"In a few short hours, a ceremony will take place in the Throne Room. He wants you there.\"</p><p>Tims puzzled over this for a moment. Still unsure, he said, \"Why would the King want me to attend this ceremony? I'm nobody important.\"</p><p>Averin practically laughed. \"Because! He's going to name you his personal squire!\"</p><p>Tims almost fell backwards into his bed. His mouth opened and tried to form words but they couldn't come out. The words just didn't register with his brain as logical or real.</p><p>Averin fixed her gaze on him earnestly. \"I want to make certain this is something you want, Tims. It means you will have a salary to do with what you will, apartments in the palace too! We can be like brother and sister!\"</p><p>A strange thing happened then. He felt a sudden ache in his chest as if he had been hit with an invisible punch. This wasn't what he wanted to hear.</p><p>\"Think of it, Tims!\" Averin was beaming.</p><p>\"I am,” he finally got the words out. \"But I'm not noble, there is no noble blood at all in these veins of mine.\"</p><p>Averin shrugged. \"That's why father is breaking tradition. He wants you with us. He says he owes you more than a place as a stable hand. He sees something in you. He wouldn't have planned this otherwise.\"</p><p>Tims blinked and the last remaining signs of sleep vanished. \"A squire, huh?\" He laughed softly. Him, a nobody born of nobody important being so close to the King of Calmone. What he would give to see Brad's face now.</p><p>Averin paused and looked a bit concerned. \"I mean, it's not going to be easy. It will actually be a lot of work. You will have to do lessons like me, be tutored in etiquette, in letters, all of that boring stuff. But I know you can do it. I have seen you and how you work.\"</p><p>Tims shook his head with another laugh. \"You planned this, didn't you?\"</p><p>Averin shrugged. \"I might have had a hand in it along the way. That is all.\"</p><p>He lifted his head to the ceiling. \"What have you gotten me into, girl?\"</p><p>\"Is that a yes then?\" she smiled. \"If not, tell me and I will let father know. We won't go through with it.\"</p><p>He laughed again because that's all he could do. There were too many emotions swimming around to know what he really felt. He couldn't think clearly. \"It's fine, Averin.\" He smiled. \"It would be an honor to serve your father.\"</p><p>Averin clapped her hands together with a soft squeal of pleasure. \"Perfect!\" She got up from the bed and turned to go. Pausing, she turned back around and leaning in, kissed his forehead gently. \"Thank you for ...being you.\" She smiled and hurriedly to the door and left.</p><p>Tims slowly reached up and touched his forehead. Warring emotions flooded through him as he stared out at nothing.</p><p>When at last he could lay back down, he couldn't get back to sleep. He lay awake wondering.</p><p>A squire! King Joshua's personal squire! Nowhere in all his most imaginable dreams did this take place!&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>",
